    How to choose your best battle team (6-Pokemon)?

    Generated on 2025-08-28

    1. Goal, dataset & preprocessing

    The objective is to build the best six‑Pokémon battle team by explicitly balancing multivariate tradeoffs: raw power, defensive staying power, speed control, and type coverage while avoiding redundancy. The dataset is a roster of 800 Pokémon with standard stat columns (HP, Attack, Sp. Atk, Defense, Sp. Def, Speed, Total) plus Type 1/Type 2, name and flags; known quirks include many missing Type 2 values (386 rows, 48.2%), inconsistent naming (SP Atk / SP Def casing and stray whitespace), and variant forms recorded as single name strings. Minimal cleaning steps are: parse numeric stats into numeric types, trim and normalize name and type strings, coerce Type 2 missing entries to None, and export a derived dataset. Immediate derived fields to compute before analysis are Offensive_balance (combined Attack + Sp. Atk signal), Defensive_balance (combined Defense + Sp. Def), Bulk_index (HP multiplied by Defensive_balance), Speed tier buckets (slow <50, mid 50–100, fast >100), and a glass‑cannon flag (high Speed but low combined defenses). These derived fields make team tradeoffs explicit and readable for both players and visualization workflows.

    The visual panel shows the roster’s Total stat distribution and a comparative boxplot of Offensive vs Defensive balance, revealing the broad scale of available power and the typical tradeoffs between attacking and defending. Totals span a wide range (min 180, max 780) with mean ≈435 and median 450, indicating many mid‑power Pokémon but clear outliers at both ends (legendary Mega/Primal forms occupy the top). Offensive_balance and Defensive_balance center around roughly 76 and 73 respectively with wide variance, and the boxplots expose that offensive extremes are more common than extreme defensive outliers; this helps explain why extreme attackers (e.g., Mega Rayquaza, Deoxys Attack) coexist with very bulky outliers (e.g., Blissey). The missing Type 2 rate (~48%) and the Total distribution skew inform normalization and binning choices for downstream charts.

    2. Key metrics and feature engineering

    Primary team‑construction metrics capture what players care about and what visualizations should surface: raw Total and per‑stat roles (HP, Atk, Sp. Atk, Def, Sp. Def, Speed) determine immediate roles; Offensive_balance and Defensive_balance summarize a Pokémon’s leaning; Bulk_index (HP × Defensive_balance) quantifies staying power; Speed tiers distinguish tempo roles (slow/mid/fast); a glass‑cannon flag highlights fast but frail attackers; and Type coverage measures team matchups across 18 types. Useful transformations include per‑stat z‑scores and percentiles to compare across scales, composite role scores (weighted sums of normalized stats) to rank candidates for a given role, and rank‑percentile buckets for interactive sliders. Always run correlation checks (e.g., Offensive vs Defensive correlation ≈0.49) and inspect distributions to decide whether to log‑transform or clamp extreme values before aggregating or visual encoding.

    A multivariate scatter uses size to represent Bulk_index, color for speed tier, and shape for the glass‑cannon flag to show how tempo, bulk, and offensive/defensive balances co‑exist. The data show mid‑speed Pokémon dominate (≈60%), with slow ≈27% and fast ≈13%; glass‑cannon candidates are rare (9 Pokémon, ~1.1%). Bulk_index separates clear tanks (Blissey, Giratina, Lugia, Cresselia) from glassy speedsters (Deoxys forms, Ninjask, Accelgor), and correlations reveal that Total and Bulk are strongly associated with Offensive_balance (Total vs Off r≈0.888) and Bulk vs Defensive_balance (r≈0.783), so size and x/y placement together help pick role complements.

    3. Archetypes, role discovery & visual encodings

    Archetypes map cleanly to stat signatures: physical and special sweepers show high single‑side Offensive_balance with high Speed or Attack/Sp. Atk, mixed attackers balance both offensive stats, physical and special walls show elevated Defense or Sp. Def and high Bulk_index, pivots/supports trade some raw power for utility stats and middling bulk, and hazard setters typically sit in mid speed with high defenses. Clustering and dimensionality reduction help surface these patterns: radar/star glyphs are intuitive for single‑team role summaries, parallel coordinates and scatter matrices reveal tradeoffs across Attack vs Sp. Atk and Defense vs Sp. Def, and PCA/clustering discovers natural role groups for suggestion engines. Surface glass‑cannons and tanks visually by combining shape (flag), color (speed tier), and size (bulk); this makes it straightforward to assemble complementary teammates that cover each other’s weaknesses.

    PCA + cluster scatter shows four natural archetype clusters (k=4) with distinct centroids and type patterns. Cluster 0 (89 Pokémon) combines very high offensive and defensive balances and the largest Bulk_index (centroid Off≈119, Def≈103, Bulk≈9838, Speed≈97) — these look like high‑end heavy hitters and versatile legendaries. Cluster 1 (225) is mid‑offense, moderate defence and bulk (Off≈87, Def≈72, Bulk≈5050) and includes many Normal/Electric/Fire primaries — good mixed attackers and sweep candidates. Cluster 2 (180) is defense‑leaning and bulky with lower Speed (Off≈80, Def≈95, Bulk≈7740, Speed≈51), matching tanks and walls. Cluster 3 (306) contains many low‑to‑mid stat Pokémon with the smallest Bulk_index and lower offensive/defensive scores, representing common utility or frail species. Glass‑cannon incidence is concentrated in Cluster 1 (~4%) while other clusters have virtually none; speed‑tier proportions per cluster help designers and players pick complementary teammates (e.g., Cluster 0 contains many fast threats, Cluster 2 many slow tanks). Visual encodings that combine cluster color, bulk size and glass‑flag shape make archetype selection actionable.

    4. Team construction workflow & interactive dashboard

    A practical workflow for building a six‑Pokémon team starts with (1) picking one or two core attackers or a win condition, (2) adding checks and counters by scanning primary and secondary type weaknesses, (3) ensuring speed control and hazard management (lead, hazard setter, hazard remover, and speed tiers), (4) balancing bulk and the special/physical mix to avoid one‑sided teams, and (5) finalizing with type coverage and redundancy checks. A dashboard should include multi‑select filters for Type 1/2, sliders for stat thresholds (suggested default speed slider ≈60 near the roster median 65), a drag‑and‑drop team builder with a live type‑coverage meter and pairwise mutual weakness matrix, and a team score summary showing coverage, median speed and team bulk. Automated suggestions can run a greedy algorithm (maximize marginal type coverage or aggregate utility) or a constrained optimizer (maximize team utility under slot and type redundancy constraints).

    The suggestion panel ranks Pokémon by a composite suggestion score that mixes speed and bulk thresholds with offensive potential; top candidates vary by objective but examples illustrate common choices. Most common primary types are Water (112), Normal (98), Grass (70), Bug (69), Psychic (57) and Fire (52), so the suggestion engine must counter heavy Water/Normal representation. Median Speed is 65 and median Bulk_index is 4800 (Q1=2925, Q3=7140), so sensible default sliders let users tighten selections; offensive‑heavy picks (Rayquaza Mega, Deoxys Attack, Mewtwo Megas) and bulky picks (Blissey, Giratina, Lugia, Cresselia) appear clearly in the ranked suggestions, and a balanced set (Kyogre Primal, Groudon Primal, Rayquaza Mega, Mewtwo Mega X) shows how the system surfaces tradeoffs between raw offense and lasting durability.

    5. Evaluation, benchmarks & reproducibility

    Objective evaluation requires repeatable component scores: type_coverage (fraction of opponent types countered), balance_score (dispersion across team offense vs defense), bulk_score (aggregate Bulk_index normalized by team size), speed_composition (counts in slow/mid/fast buckets and median speed), and an aggregate team_utility (weighted sum of normalized components). Benchmarks for recommendation systems include A/B tests on human‑curated teams, simulated matchups if a battle engine is available, and cross‑validation of automated suggestions against historical competitive team lists. For reproducibility, record exact cleaning steps (trim/normalize types, fill Type 2 with None), formulas for derived features, and random seeds for clustering or sampling; the derived dataset has been saved to pokemon_derived_team_features.csv and all analyses were run on the 800‑row roster.

    A stacked component view of normalized contributions illustrates how offense, defense, bulk and speed combine into an aggregate utility score and which components dominate top candidates. Normalized component means are Off≈0.388, Def≈0.261, Bulk≈0.284, Speed≈0.362 with an aggregate utility mean ≈0.326, and the highest aggregate utility Pokémon include Kyogre Primal and Groudon Primal (agg≈0.70), Mega Rayquaza (≈0.693), and Mewtwo Megas (≈0.68–0.69). The visualization makes it easy to spot glass‑cannon candidates (high speed but low defense contribution) versus bulky candidates (high bulk contribution), and to filter to the 81 Pokémon in the top decile of Bulk_index or the 106 speed‑lead candidates when assembling complementary teams.
